WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:28.000
Okay, welcome everybody to this evening's anti-debate.

00:28.000 --> 00:35.600
As you know, I'm Jonathan Rouson, I'm Director of Prospectiva and the anti-debate process

00:35.600 --> 00:40.560
has been funded by the John Templeton Foundation to give us two years to create this thing.

00:40.560 --> 00:44.140
And we're currently a few months into that, so what you're about to observe is a kind

00:44.140 --> 00:48.120
of toddler rather than a fully fledged adolescent or adult.

00:48.120 --> 00:51.840
It's something in the process of creation, but let me say a little bit at the beginning

00:51.840 --> 00:57.520
before we start about why we're doing it and what it's about.

00:57.520 --> 00:58.520
It has its place.

00:58.520 --> 01:04.680
The debate can be beautiful, edifying, it's often a spectacle, a clash, entertaining,

01:04.680 --> 01:09.640
it's often very enlivening, it's done well, it can even be informative.

01:09.640 --> 01:16.000
But sadly, the way the world is today, there's many structural incentives towards polarization

01:16.000 --> 01:22.080
built into the way we get our information, not just our papers, but the channels we watch,

01:22.080 --> 01:27.320
the social media feeds that we have algorithmically being done to us, means that on any given

01:27.320 --> 01:32.440
issue we're less likely to see it in the round and more likely to see it in a way that reinforces

01:32.440 --> 01:33.440
our biases.

01:33.440 --> 01:39.280
So we're in a phase of history where divergence and bifurcation and disagreement is actually

01:39.280 --> 01:46.240
being compounded and exacerbated by the systems and structures that prevail.

01:46.240 --> 01:53.280
And this is a big deal because democracies or even any functioning form of government

01:53.280 --> 01:59.760
that includes people relies on a capacity to discuss adequately what's going on.

01:59.760 --> 02:05.160
It relies on a sense-making process, if you like, a meaning-making process.

02:05.160 --> 02:10.680
And debate was the sort of high end of what it was like to observe a culture talking to

02:10.680 --> 02:11.680
itself.

02:11.680 --> 02:12.920
So there will be a future for debate.

02:12.920 --> 02:16.640
It's not that we're against all forms of it, but we do think there's a case for trying

02:16.640 --> 02:18.880
to develop something radically new.

02:18.880 --> 02:26.480
I would say that the key idea to grasp here is that whereas debate is primarily about opposing

02:26.480 --> 02:32.000
views in which the center of inquiry is somehow in the middle of the room and people are trying

02:32.000 --> 02:34.280
to figure out who's winning, which side am I on?

02:34.280 --> 02:36.680
That's sort of debate classically conceived.

02:37.520 --> 02:44.040
But we live in a time where we're all exposed to things that we struggle to make sense of,

02:44.040 --> 02:46.760
moments where we can't quite agree with ourselves.

02:46.760 --> 02:49.040
Our values don't always align with our actions.

02:49.040 --> 02:51.720
Our ideas don't always chime with our values.

02:51.720 --> 02:55.000
And a lot of what the anti-debates are getting at is that internal struggle.

02:55.000 --> 02:58.800
And it's a struggle you'll see between us on stage, probably, but it's also one we want

02:58.800 --> 03:00.520
you to experience, too.

03:00.520 --> 03:03.120
It's about finding your own inner center in a relationship.

03:03.120 --> 03:05.240
So what are we trying to achieve at the end of it?

03:05.240 --> 03:08.280
It's not some beautiful middle position in which everyone can agree on.

03:08.280 --> 03:10.600
It's not some consensus verdict.

03:10.600 --> 03:14.480
It's a deeper felt sense of your relationship to the issue of hand.

03:14.480 --> 03:16.320
And another beauty is that we don't know what the issue is yet.

03:16.320 --> 03:18.320
We're about to find out.

03:18.320 --> 03:19.320
Thank you.

